msgid "Understanding ROS 2 nodes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Understanding-ROS2-Nodes.rst:6
msgid ""
"**Goal:** Learn about the function of nodes in ROS 2, and the tools to "
"interact with them."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Understanding-ROS2-Nodes.rst:8
msgid "**Tutorial level:** Beginner"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Understanding-ROS2-Nodes.rst:10
msgid "**Time:** 10 minutes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Understanding-ROS2-Nodes.rst:14
msgid "Contents"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Understanding-ROS2-Nodes.rst:17
msgid "Background"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Understanding-ROS2-Nodes.rst:20
msgid "1 The ROS 2 graph"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Understanding-ROS2-Nodes.rst:22
msgid ""
"Over the next few tutorials, you will learn about a series of core ROS 2 "
"concepts that make up what is referred to as the “ROS (2) graph”."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Understanding-ROS2-Nodes.rst:24
msgid ""
"The ROS graph is a network of ROS 2 elements processing data together at one "
"time. It encompasses all executables and the connections between them if you "
"were to map them all out and visualize them."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Understanding-ROS2-Nodes.rst:28
msgid "2 Nodes in ROS 2"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Understanding-ROS2-Nodes.rst:30
msgid ""
"Each node in ROS should be responsible for a single, module purpose (e.g. "
"one node for controlling wheel motors, one node for controlling a laser "
"range-finder, etc). Each node can send and receive data to other nodes via "
"topics, services, actions, or parameters."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Understanding-ROS2-Nodes.rst:35
msgid ""
"A full robotic system is comprised of many nodes working in concert. In ROS "
"2, a single executable (C++ program, Python program, etc.) can contain one "
"or more nodes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Understanding-ROS2-Nodes.rst:39
msgid "Prerequisites"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Understanding-ROS2-Nodes.rst:41
msgid ""
"The :ref:`previous tutorial <Turtlesim>` shows you how to install the "
"``turtlesim`` package used here."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Understanding-ROS2-Nodes.rst:43
msgid ""
"As always, don’t forget to source ROS 2 in :ref:`every new terminal you open "
"<ConfigROS2>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Understanding-ROS2-Nodes.rst:46
msgid "Tasks"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Understanding-ROS2-Nodes.rst:49
msgid "1 ros2 run"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Understanding-ROS2-Nodes.rst:51
msgid "The command ``ros2 run`` launches an executable from a package."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Understanding-ROS2-Nodes.rst:53
msgid "ros2 run <package_name> <executable_name>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Understanding-ROS2-Nodes.rst:57
msgid "To run turtlesim, open a new terminal, and enter the following command:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Understanding-ROS2-Nodes.rst:59
msgid "ros2 run turtlesim turtlesim_node"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Understanding-ROS2-Nodes.rst:63
msgid "The turtlesim window will open, as you saw in the previous tutorial."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Understanding-ROS2-Nodes.rst:65
msgid ""
"Here, the package name is ``turtlesim`` and the executable name is "
"``turtlesim_node``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Understanding-ROS2-Nodes.rst:67
msgid ""
"We still don’t know the node name, however. You can find node names by using "
"``ros2 node list``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Understanding-ROS2-Nodes.rst:71
msgid "2 ros2 node list"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Understanding-ROS2-Nodes.rst:73
msgid ""
"``ros2 node list`` will show you the names of all running nodes. This is "
"especially useful when you want to interact with a node, or when you have a "
"system running many nodes and need to keep track of them."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Understanding-ROS2-Nodes.rst:76
msgid ""
"Open a new terminal while turtlesim is still running in the other one, and "
"enter the following command:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Understanding-ROS2-Nodes.rst:78
msgid "ros2 node list"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Understanding-ROS2-Nodes.rst:82
msgid "The terminal will return the node name:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Understanding-ROS2-Nodes.rst:84
msgid "/turtlesim"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Understanding-ROS2-Nodes.rst:88
msgid "Open another new terminal and start the teleop node with the command:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Understanding-ROS2-Nodes.rst:90
msgid "ros2 run turtlesim turtle_teleop_key"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Understanding-ROS2-Nodes.rst:94
msgid ""
"Here, we are searching the ``turtlesim`` package again, this time for the "
"executable named ``turtle_teleop_key``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Understanding-ROS2-Nodes.rst:96
msgid ""
"Return to the terminal where you ran ``ros2 node list`` and run it again. "
"You will now see the names of two active nodes:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Understanding-ROS2-Nodes.rst:99
msgid ""
"/turtlesim\n"
"/teleop_turtle"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Understanding-ROS2-Nodes.rst:105
msgid "2.1 Remapping"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Understanding-ROS2-Nodes.rst:107
msgid ""
"`Remapping <https://design.ros2.org/articles/ros_command_line_arguments."
"html#name-remapping-rules>`__ allows you to reassign default node "
"properties, like node name, topic names, service names, etc., to custom "
"values. In the last tutorial, you used remapping on ``turtle_teleop_key`` to "
"change the default turtle being controlled."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Understanding-ROS2-Nodes.rst:110
msgid ""
"Now, lets reassign the name of our ``/turtlesim`` node. In a new terminal, "
"run the following command:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Understanding-ROS2-Nodes.rst:113
msgid "ros2 run turtlesim turtlesim_node --ros-args --remap __node:=my_turtle"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Understanding-ROS2-Nodes.rst:118
msgid ""
"Since you’re calling ``ros2 run`` on turtlesim again, another turtlesim "
"window will open. However, now if you return to the terminal where you ran "
"``ros2 node list``, and run it again, you will see three node names:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Understanding-ROS2-Nodes.rst:121
msgid ""
"/turtlesim\n"
"/teleop_turtle\n"
"/my_turtle"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Understanding-ROS2-Nodes.rst:128
msgid "3 ros2 node info"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Understanding-ROS2-Nodes.rst:130
msgid ""
"Now that you know the names of your nodes, you can access more information "
"about them with:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Understanding-ROS2-Nodes.rst:132
msgid "ros2 node info <node_name>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Understanding-ROS2-Nodes.rst:136
msgid "To examine your latest node, ``my_turtle``, run the following command:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Understanding-ROS2-Nodes.rst:138
msgid "ros2 node info /my_turtle"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Understanding-ROS2-Nodes.rst:142
msgid ""
"``ros2 node info`` returns a list of subscribers, publishers, services, and "
"actions (the ROS graph connections) that interact with that node. The output "
"should look like this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Understanding-ROS2-Nodes.rst:145
msgid ""
"/my_turtle\n"
"  Subscribers:\n"
"    /parameter_events: rcl_interfaces/msg/ParameterEvent\n"
"    /turtle1/cmd_vel: geometry_msgs/msg/Twist\n"
"  Publishers:\n"
"    /parameter_events: rcl_interfaces/msg/ParameterEvent\n"
"    /rosout: rcl_interfaces/msg/Log\n"
"    /turtle1/color_sensor: turtlesim/msg/Color\n"
"    /turtle1/pose: turtlesim/msg/Pose\n"
"  Services:\n"
"    /clear: std_srvs/srv/Empty\n"
"    /kill: turtlesim/srv/Kill\n"
"    /reset: std_srvs/srv/Empty\n"
"    /spawn: turtlesim/srv/Spawn\n"
"    /turtle1/set_pen: turtlesim/srv/SetPen\n"
"    /turtle1/teleport_absolute: turtlesim/srv/TeleportAbsolute\n"
"    /turtle1/teleport_relative: turtlesim/srv/TeleportRelative\n"
"    /my_turtle/describe_parameters: rcl_interfaces/srv/DescribeParameters\n"
"    /my_turtle/get_parameter_types: rcl_interfaces/srv/GetParameterTypes\n"
"    /my_turtle/get_parameters: rcl_interfaces/srv/GetParameters\n"
"    /my_turtle/list_parameters: rcl_interfaces/srv/ListParameters\n"
"    /my_turtle/set_parameters: rcl_interfaces/srv/SetParameters\n"
"    /my_turtle/set_parameters_atomically: rcl_interfaces/srv/"
"SetParametersAtomically\n"
"  Action Servers:\n"
"    /turtle1/rotate_absolute: turtlesim/action/RotateAbsolute\n"
"  Action Clients:"
msgstr ""

